Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Atomic Spectroscopy", "Section",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9183792045139885`*^9, 
  3.9183792103365145`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"953b915d-acf3-44d6-8f94-\
d1281449b4d3"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["\<\
Testing Our Results from the Time-Independent Schr\[ODoubleDot]dinger Equation\
\>", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9183792140628815`*^9, 
  3.918379238605643*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"ecbb2bae-0546-4c45-ac1c-\
db862d7eba69"],

Cell["\<\
How do we know that the predictions that we obtain from the time-independent \
Schr\[ODoubleDot]dinger equation are correct? How do we know the \
approximations we have made in the Hartree-Fock approximation are \
sufficiently accurate? There are many experimental methods to probe the \
structure of atoms, but spectroscopy is one of the oldest, simplest, and most \
common techniques. Here we define spectroscopy as the measurement of spectra \
resulting from matter (in this case atoms) interacting with or emitting light.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9183792411979485`*^9, 
  3.918379573463586*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"948b4b97-ec2f-4c79-955d-\
5adddc873a05"],

Cell["\<\
A relatively simple approach to studying electron behavior in atoms is \
provided by atomic emission spectroscopy. Heating atoms in a flame or plasma \
provides energy input into the atoms that leads to the electrons occupying \
higher-energy states (higher-energy orbitals). These excited electrons then \
transition back to lower-energy states, and a photon is emitted with an \
energy equal to the difference in energy between the high-energy initial \
state and the lower-energy final state. Because these photons have different \
energy depending on the transition, they also have different wavelengths, so \
measuring the emission spectrum reveals the allowed energy levels (the \
energies of the atomic orbitals) of the electrons in the atom.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.918379675437809*^9, 
  3.918380071031559*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"174b3092-38eb-4f3a-971d-\
09c1a6d9cd7f"],

Cell["\<\
Shown in Figure 8.1 are atomic emission spectra of alkali and alkaline-earth \
atoms in the visible region of the electromagnetic spectrum. The background \
coloring from blue to red gives the approximate wavelength of the light, and \
the bright lines in the spectra represent the emission wavelengths. Notice \
that each atom has a distinct set of emission bands, which means that these \
emission spectra can be used to assess which atoms are present in a sample. \
Similar results could be obtained by instead irradiating a vaporized atomic \
sample and measuring absorption of the light.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9183804059065065`*^9, 3.918380574565652*^9}, {
  3.9183808196509066`*^9, 
  3.9183808676170464`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"f581d00c-30f2-44b0-afc1-\
6500d4806e74"],

