Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Figure 8.3",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 ". Simplified atomic transitions of the sodium atom. Orci, Wikimedia, 2007, \
CC-BY-SA 3.0, \
https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Energy_levels_of_sodium_atom.png"
}], "Affiliation",
 CellChangeTimes->CompressedData["
1:eJxTTMoPSmViYGAQBmIQPeNH5qbXiW8cy6t7doDoiRfCxd8A6ZBDtWA6NlRg
2Ucgzeepug5EP9i1klMq+Y3jPDdZHhB9wJqvywxIZ3gETwDRKatTZoDo3bMc
Z4L5eheOmQPpsjc+p0C0n5/FRRDdenT2FRAdtplH9g2QPiRrCqbDLvOkxqa8
cdwf4dAAopc8eDIFRO/S+DoVROte8dgGoucZ7NoJoo9Z7LkBogumMN4F0V3b
ggPNMt44im+qA9PVp4vCQPS2YpFwEF223e7odsO3jh0/+i+CaI6KNWw7gLTO
Y1leEJ21y+s8iH5jFwWmd0jp3gfRL0LUX4BoAOmEmFw=
  "],ExpressionUUID->"b15832d6-d741-48bf-bf66-a58a9a42aa5e"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Although in a simple picture we can think of these spectra as resulting \
from an electron moving between atomic orbitals, ",
 StyleBox["this depiction is not sufficient to fully explain the observed \
atomic spectra",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 ". This result is observed for two reasons: first, not all transitions \
between different energy levels are allowed. In other words, there are ",
 StyleBox["selection rules",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " that arise from properties of the atom and photon that dictate which \
changes of an electron\[CloseCurlyQuote]s energy level are likely to occur. \
These allowed transitions are roughly depicted in Figure 8.3 by the distinct \
arrow colors. The second reason is more complex; in short, simply knowing the \
electron configuration is not sufficient to fully describe the state of an \
atom. For example, for the first excited state of helium ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"(", 
    RowBox[{"1", 
     SuperscriptBox["s", "1"], "2", 
     SuperscriptBox["s", "1"]}], ")"}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "07033401-2363-4b46-a6fa-44e320de5c56"],
 ", there are multiple possible configurations of the electron spin that lead \
to distinct states. To fully explain atomic spectra, and thus to describe the \
fundamental properties of atoms, we need to further specify the electronic \
state of an atom. A systematic nomenclature, known as term symbols, is used \
for this purpose."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.918382926278092*^9, 3.918382935914171*^9}, {
  3.9183830024507074`*^9, 3.918383339234105*^9}, {3.918383385961699*^9, 
  3.9183834324583187`*^9}, {3.918383734140606*^9, 3.918383860129142*^9}, {
  3.918403142769271*^9, 
  3.9184031460786715`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"51febd8f-93ef-42a6-bb56-\
b86e28dd0221"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Term Symbols", "Section",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.812725644444974*^9, 3.8127256467067165`*^9}, {
  3.812726855085826*^9, 
  3.812726859553876*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"a64201ad-9d0f-4d4e-bf85-\
e2738b64aff4"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["The Angular Momentum of Molecules", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8127326684697275`*^9, 3.8127326702742815`*^9}, {
  3.812732705569374*^9, 
  3.8127327103348064`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"3321a722-e455-4bcc-afd3-\
01016ca37241"],

Cell["\<\
We have now seen that we can (approximately) describe each electron in our \
multielectron atom by a specific spin orbital, the spatial component of which \
bears a resemblance to the corresponding orbital of the hydrogen atom. \
Remember that, for the hydrogen atom, each of these orbitals had a specific \
orbital angular momentum, with the magnitude of the square of the orbital \
angular momentum given by\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8127327152815866`*^9, 3.8127328697037916`*^9}, {
  3.812732940324016*^9, 3.812732943164544*^9}, {3.812733237375738*^9, 
  3.812733238822556*^9}, {3.81273335771198*^9, 
  3.8127334051009507`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"a4ead268-c304-45a0-a1ba-\
c2521031a6ff"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    SuperscriptBox["\[HBar]", "2"], 
    FormBox[
     RowBox[{"l", "(", 
      RowBox[{"l", "+", "1"}], ")"}],
     TraditionalForm], "          ", 
    StyleBox["l",
     FontSlant->"Italic"]}], "=", "0"}], ",", "1", ",", "2", ",", "...", " ", 
  ",", 
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["n",
    FontSlant->"Italic"], 
   StyleBox["-",
    FontSlant->"Plain"], 
   StyleBox["1",
    FontSlant->"Plain"], 
   StyleBox["   ",
    FontSlant->"Plain"]}]}]], "DisplayFormulaNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.810112811439228*^9, 3.8101128248442793`*^9}, {
   3.810479494926491*^9, 3.8104795038498344`*^9}, {3.810479572543576*^9, 
