f62963069df4"],

Cell["\<\
In addition, we saw that each electron has a spin angular momentum, with the \
magnitude of the square of the spin angular momentum given by \
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.812733025393682*^9, 3.8127330572634726`*^9}, {
   3.8127330887237496`*^9, 3.8127331145441713`*^9}, 
   3.9184032443176003`*^9},ExpressionUUID->"64f8f797-e91e-40d8-b235-\
d508f78b0144"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["s",
    FontSlant->"Italic"], 
   RowBox[{"(", 
    RowBox[{
     StyleBox["s",
      FontSlant->"Italic"], "+", "1"}], ")"}], 
   SuperscriptBox["\[HBar]", "2"]}], "=", 
  RowBox[{
   FractionBox["1", "2"], 
   RowBox[{"(", 
    RowBox[{
     FractionBox["1", "2"], "+", "1"}], ")"}], 
   SuperscriptBox["\[HBar]", "2"]}]}]], "DisplayFormulaNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8124635845256133`*^9, 3.812463659917937*^9}, {
   3.8124637556855745`*^9, 3.8124637660754547`*^9}, {3.812465075219303*^9, 
   3.8124650843093405`*^9}, {3.812465116115116*^9, 3.8124651327747536`*^9}, {
   3.8124761533249984`*^9, 3.8124761561504664`*^9}, 
   3.8127338499945855`*^9},ExpressionUUID->"d6d5afa3-9ff4-4f92-925e-\
7c5c5cb2cb06"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "and the magnitude of the ",
 StyleBox["z ",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "component of the spin angular momentum given by"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.812733121133623*^9, 3.812733125920349*^9}, {
  3.812733250094678*^9, 
  3.8127332564092216`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"fca4b5f5-dcf9-4ddf-ba87-\
3d943ed24ac3"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   SubscriptBox[
    StyleBox["m",
     FontSlant->"Italic"], "s"], "\[HBar]"}], "=", 
  RowBox[{"\[PlusMinus]", 
   FractionBox["\[HBar]", "2"]}]}]], "DisplayFormulaNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8124635845256133`*^9, 3.812463659917937*^9}, {
   3.8124637556855745`*^9, 3.8124637660754547`*^9}, {3.812465075219303*^9, 
   3.8124651077684402`*^9}, 
   3.812733852490324*^9},ExpressionUUID->"a0be5042-0b85-4113-88da-\
c5d3049a0e26"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "But what if we want to know the angular momentum of an atom containing \
multiple electrons? Well, it turns out that we can add the angular momentum \
contribution from each spin orbital state. However, this task is not as \
straightforward as it might at first seem. Remember that angular momentum is \
a vector quantity. In addition, since we constrain the ",
 StyleBox["z",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " component of both orbital and spin angular momentum, the ",
 StyleBox["x",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " and ",
 StyleBox["y",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " components are completely unspecified. Remember that we depicted the \
orbital angular momentum for the hydrogen atom in angular momentum vector \
space as shown in Figure 8.4."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.812733294282079*^9, 3.8127333506977315`*^9}, {
  3.8127334247246647`*^9, 3.8127335664449277`*^9}, {3.8129041096537404`*^9, 
  3.812904110269494*^9}, {3.918403288600181*^9, 3.918403306231533*^9}, {
  3.9184054085996485`*^9, 
  3.9184054104141874`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"476a6872-3000-44a6-9367-\
18659df68e49"],

